<caml:Description xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><caml:Id>20110SB__106799INT</caml:Id><caml:VersionNum>99</caml:VersionNum><caml:History><caml:Action><caml:ActionText>INTRODUCED</caml:ActionText><caml:ActionDate>2012-02-13</caml:ActionDate></caml:Action><caml:Action><caml:ActionText>CORRECTED</caml:ActionText><caml:ActionDate>2012-02-15</caml:ActionDate></caml:Action></caml:History><caml:LegislativeInfo><caml:SessionYear>2011</caml:SessionYear><caml:SessionNum>0</caml:SessionNum><caml:MeasureType>SB</caml:MeasureType><caml:MeasureNum>1067</caml:MeasureNum><caml:MeasureState>INT</caml:MeasureState></caml:LegislativeInfo><caml:AuthorText authorType="LEAD_AUTHOR">Introduced by Senator La Malfa</caml:AuthorText><caml:AuthorText authorType="COAUTHOR_OPPOSITE">(Coauthor: Assembly Member Nielsen)</caml:AuthorText><caml:Authors><caml:Legislator><caml:Contribution>LEAD_AUTHOR</caml:Contribution><caml:House>SENATE</caml:House><caml:Name>La Malfa</caml:Name></caml:Legislator><caml:Legislator><caml:Contribution>COAUTHOR</caml:Contribution><caml:House>ASSEMBLY</caml:House><caml:Name>Nielsen</caml:Name></caml:Legislator></caml:Authors><caml:Title> An act to amend Section 830.39 of the Penal Code, and to amend Section 2403.5 of the Vehicle Code, relating to peace officers. </caml:Title><caml:GeneralSubject><caml:Subject>Peace officers: interstate cooperation.</caml:Subject></caml:GeneralSubject><caml:DigestText><p>Existing law authorizes any regularly employed law enforcement officer of the Oregon State Police, the Nevada Department of Motor Vehicles and Public Safety, or the Arizona Department of Public Safety to be a peace officer in this state if all of certain conditions are met, including, but not limited to, the out-of-state officer is providing law enforcement services in response to a request for services initiated by a member of the California Highway Patrol, providing law enforcement services for the purpose of assisting a member of the California Highway Patrol, as provided, and a reciprocal operational agreement is in effect between the Department of the California Highway Patrol and the law enforcement officer’s out-of-state agency.</p><p>This bill would expand the scope of these provisions to include any regularly employed law enforcement officer within the State of Oregon, the State of Nevada, or the State of Arizona and
		a California peace officer, as defined, and, with regard to the reciprocal operational agreements, expand the scope of these provisions to include the head of an authorized California law enforcement agency, or a designated representative, and authorized representatives of law enforcement agencies within the State of Oregon, the State of Nevada, or the State of Arizona. The bill would also make conforming changes. </p></caml:DigestText><caml:DigestKey><caml:VoteRequired>MAJORITY</caml:VoteRequired><caml:Appropriation>NO</caml:Appropriation><caml:FiscalCommittee>YES</caml:FiscalCommittee><caml:LocalProgram>NO</caml:LocalProgram><caml:Urgency>NO</caml:Urgency><caml:TaxLevy>NO</caml:TaxLevy><caml:DeclaringUrgency>NO</caml:DeclaringUrgency></caml:DigestKey></caml:Description><caml:Bill id="bill" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><caml:Preamble>The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</caml:Preamble><caml:BillSection id="id_57175150-1918-4075-B060-29CB78B3BDAC"><caml:Num>SECTION 1.</caml:Num><caml:ActionLine action="IS_AMENDED" xlink:type="locator" xlink:href="urn:caml:codes:PEN:caml#xpointer(%2Fcaml%3ALawDoc%2Fcaml%3ACode%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'PART'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'2.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'TITLE'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'3.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'CHAPTER'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'4.5.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawSection%5Bcaml%3ANum%3D'830.39.'%5D)" xlink:label="fractionType: LAW_SECTION">Section 830.39 of the <caml:DocName>Penal Code</caml:DocName> is amended to read:</caml:ActionLine><caml:Fragment><caml:LawSection id="id_27BE9884-E7A5-4A3D-AAA7-CBB60F7217A9"><caml:Num>830.39.</caml:Num><caml:LawSectionVersion id="id_48319AF6-47BA-4127-93A1-AD56DC17DAEF"><caml:Content><p>(a)<span class="EnSpace"/>Any regularly employed law enforcement officer<?xm-deletion_mark data=" of the Oregon State Police, the Nevada Department of Motor Vehicles and Public Safety, or the Arizona Department of Public Safety"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> within the State of Oregon, the State of Nevada, or the State of Arizona<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> is a peace officer in this state if all of the following conditions are met:</p><p>(1)<span class="EnSpace"/>The officer is providing, or attempting to provide, law enforcement services within this state on the state or county highways and areas immediately adjacent thereto, within a distance of up to 50 statute
				  miles of the contiguous border of this state and the state employing the officer.</p><p>(2)<span class="EnSpace"/>The officer is providing, or attempting to provide, law enforcement services pursuant to either of the following:</p><p>(A)<span class="EnSpace"/>In response to a request for services initiated by a<?xm-deletion_mark data=" member of the California Highway Patrol"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> California peace officer as defined in Section 830.1 or subdivision (a) of Section 830.2<?xm-insertion_mark_end?>.</p><p>(B)<span class="EnSpace"/>In response to a reasonable belief that emergency law enforcement services are necessary for the preservation of life, and a request for services by a<?xm-deletion_mark data=" member of the Department of the California Highway Patrol"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?>
				  California peace officer, as defined in Section 830.1 or subdivision (a) of Section 830.2,<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> is impractical to obtain under the circumstances. In those situations, the officer shall obtain authorization as soon as practical.</p><p>(3)<span class="EnSpace"/>The officer is providing, or attempting to provide, law enforcement services for the purpose of assisting a<?xm-deletion_mark data=" member of the California Highway Patrol"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> California peace officer, as defined in Section 830.1 or subdivision (a) of Section 830.2,<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> to provide emergency service in response to misdemeanor or felony criminal activity, pursuant to the authority of a peace officer as provided in<?xm-insertion_mark_start?> Section 830.1 or<?xm-insertion_mark_end?>
				  subdivision (a) of Section 830.2, or, in the event of highway-related traffic accidents, emergency incidents or other similar public safety problems, whether or not a<?xm-deletion_mark data=" member of the California Highway Patrol"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> California peace officer, as defined in Section 830.1 or subdivision (a) of Section 830.2,<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> is present at the scene of the event. Nothing in this section shall be construed to confer upon the officer the authority to enforce traffic or motor vehicle infractions.</p><p>(4)<span class="EnSpace"/>An agreement pursuant to Section 2403.5 of the Vehicle Code is in effect between<?xm-deletion_mark data=" the Department of the California Highway Patrol"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?>
				  a California law enforcement agency employing California peace officers, as defined in Section 830.1 or subdivision (a) of Section 830.2,<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> and the agency of the adjoining state employing the officer, the officer acts in accordance with that agreement, and the agreement specifies that the officer and employing agency of the adjoining state shall be subject to the same civil immunities and liabilities as a peace officer and his or her employing agency in this state.</p><p>(5)<span class="EnSpace"/>The officer receives no separate compensation from this state for providing law enforcement services within this state.</p><p>(6)<span class="EnSpace"/>The adjoining state employing the officer confers similar rights and authority upon a<?xm-deletion_mark data=" member of the California Highway Patrol"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?>
				  California peace officer, as defined in Section 830.1 or subdivision (a) of Section 830.2,<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> who renders assistance within that state.</p><p>(b)<span class="EnSpace"/>Whenever, pursuant to Nevada law, a Nevada correctional officer is working or supervising Nevada inmates who are performing conservation-related projects or fire suppression duties within California, the correctional officer may maintain custody of the inmates in California, and retake any inmate who should escape in California, to the same extent as if the correctional officer were a peace officer in this state and the inmate had been committed to his or her custody in proceedings under California law.</p><p>(c)<span class="EnSpace"/>Notwithstanding any other provision of law, any person who is acting as a peace officer in this state in the manner described in this section shall be deemed to have met the requirements of Section 1031
				  of the Government Code and the selection and training standards of the Commission on Peace Officer Standards and Training if the officer has completed the basic training required for peace officers in his or her state.</p><p>(d)<span class="EnSpace"/><?xm-deletion_mark data="In no case shall a "?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?>A <?xm-insertion_mark_end?>peace officer of an adjoining state<?xm-insertion_mark_start?> shall not<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> be authorized to provide services within a California jurisdiction during any period in which the regular law enforcement agency of the jurisdiction is involved in a labor dispute.</p></caml:Content></caml:LawSectionVersion></caml:LawSection></caml:Fragment></caml:BillSection><caml:BillSection id="id_30A7FFF6-3926-40E9-B2D1-B447749DA661"><caml:Num>SEC. 2.</caml:Num><caml:ActionLine action="IS_AMENDED" xlink:type="locator" xlink:href="urn:caml:codes:VEH:caml#xpointer(%2Fcaml%3ALawDoc%2Fcaml%3ACode%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'DIVISION'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'2.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'CHAPTER'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'2.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'ARTICLE'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'3.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawSection%5Bcaml%3ANum%3D'2403.5.'%5D)" xlink:label="fractionType: LAW_SECTION">Section 2403.5 of the <caml:DocName>Vehicle Code</caml:DocName> is amended to read:</caml:ActionLine><caml:Fragment><caml:LawSection id="id_E35429C6-2076-48AD-ACC8-7C0B5BA14AB9"><caml:Num>2403.5.</caml:Num><caml:LawSectionVersion id="id_49AC1CFD-A7B5-41B1-AF04-2C6254902BE1"><caml:Content><p>The<?xm-deletion_mark data=" commissioner,"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> head of an authorized California law enforcement agency,<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> or a designated representative, may enter into reciprocal operational agreements with authorized representatives of<?xm-deletion_mark data=" the Oregon State Police, the Nevada Department of Motor Vehicles and Public Safety, and the Arizona Department of Public Safety"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> law enforcement agencies within the State of Oregon, the State of Nevada, or the State of Arizona<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> to promote
				  expeditious and effective law enforcement<?xm-deletion_mark data=" sevice"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?>
				  service<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> to the public, and assistance between<?xm-deletion_mark data=" the members of the California Highway Patrol"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> California peace officers, as defined in Section 830.1 or subdivision (a) of Section 830.2,<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> and those agencies, in areas adjacent to the borders of this state and each of the adjoining states pursuant to Section<?xm-deletion_mark data=" 830.32"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> 830.39<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> of the Penal Code. The reciprocal operational agreement shall be in writing and may cover the reciprocal<?xm-deletion_mark data=" exhange"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?>
				  exchange<?xm-insertion_mark_end?>
				  of law enforcement services, resources, facilities and any other necessary and proper matters between the<?xm-deletion_mark data=" Department of the California Highway Patrol"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> authorized California law enforcement agency<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> and the respective agency. Any agreement shall specify the involved departments, divisions, or units of the agencies, the duration and purpose of the agreement, the responsibility for damages, the method of financing any joint or cooperative undertaking, and the methods to be employed to terminate an agreement. The<?xm-deletion_mark data=" commissioner"?><?xm-insertion_mark_start?> head of the California law enforcement agency<?xm-insertion_mark_end?> may establish operational procedures in implementation
				  of any reciprocal operational agreement that are necessary to achieve the purposes of the agreement.</p></caml:Content></caml:LawSectionVersion></caml:LawSection></caml:Fragment></caml:BillSection><caml:Correction>
	 Heading—Coauthors—Line 2.</caml:Correction></caml:Bill></caml:MeasureDoc>